review_text:
This product was suggested to me from my review of [[ASIN:B00BFJGM5M Suavecito Pomade Original Hold 3-Pack]], where another customer talked about the hold. This Shiner Gold does indeed have superior hold to most anything else I've used. Your hair will stay in place all day long and then some. But what really impressed me is that it also seems to tame and soften your hair at the same time. I'm leaving this review 30 hours after applying the product and my hair still looks excellent.

It does not have a greasy texture to it nor do you get that "clumpy" feeling as Suavecito can sometimes do.

My only complaint - and it's a minor one - is the smell.

Some people don't like Suavecito's smell. I love it. It smells like cologne. As a man surely you can understand why that's a good thing. I don't find Suavecito's smell to be overpowerful, and frankly you can't smell it 2 hours later anyway.

Shiner Gold? Smells like a piña colada, the smell lingers, and I can't stand it. It is for this reason I can't apply it on my goatee; there I fall back to Suavecito. A man should not walk around smelling like fruit, I'm sorry.

review_text: I wear a lot of baseball caps and have to wash them frequently.  Running them through the washing machine they get clean but then have to be blocked to get them back into any thing resembling what they looked like before being washed. I then leave the hat in the holder and put it on a hanger and hang it in the shower overnight and by the next morning it's dry.  I don't remember what the directions that this item comes with says about how to use it as I apparently didn't keep them.  So I explained how I use it and it works just fine.  Great little device. review_text: I recently converted from an electric range to gas and needed a slimline range hood that could move a lot of air. This product fits the bill nicely. It looks good, works great, was relatively easy to install with a 7" exhaust pipe (they recommend a minimum of 6" for this airflow) and matches the new brushed stainless range very nicely. review_text:
Beatrix Lee’s life has changed.

She used to be the girl who had friends in elementary school, now she is wondering the hallways of her new middle school alone.

She used to be the apple of her parent’s eye, now she is about to have a new baby come into her once perfect trio of her family.

She used to share her poetry with the world, now she discretely taps the words against her heart as if she is protecting them from the cruelties of the world.

She used to be proud of who she was, now she is keenly aware of the stares in the hallways as everyone whispers about that “weird” girl as she walks by. 

Bea finds refuge from all the whispers and stares of her new school at the secret brick wall in the woods near her school. Bea sneaks to this wall often, and many times during the school day.

One day, she decides to hide her words in a crack in the wall. She writes her words in invisible ink to protect them further before she leaves them safely behind in the wall.

But things change when Bea returns to her secret hiding place. Her words are gone. But, in their place, there is a note. A note from someone who wrote her back.

Bea's world flips upside down once she reads the response to her secret words. Who is this mysterious person? What could they possibly want from her? Maybe, just maybe, could they be the friend she has been wishing for?

The Way to Bea, by Kat Yeh, is a great novel that depicts the challenges of transitioning from the innocence of childhood to the harsher realities of becoming a teenager. Bea’s struggles are so relatable. Every preteen knows how hard it is to figure yourself out and find true friends that love you for you, weirdness and all.

I know that when I remember my middle school years, the feelings of awkwardness and unsureness instantly flow back into my mind. I look forward to adding The Way to Bea to my classroom library because it will offer a similar story to those of my students that are struggling to figure themselves out as they too are heading towards the transitioning years of middle school.

review_text:
Don't be fooled by that awful "California Gurls" single. This album doesn't need a fluffy, Ke$ha-sounding pop tart track infused with some Snoop to promote the decency. "E.T." would have been a way better choice, (despite its sounding like it was produced by t.A.T.u).

Katy Perry is probably best described as the P!nk for the teenage girls sector. She has enough bubble gum flavor on her tracks to appeal to the younger minds but she has enough honesty and personal experience in her lyrics for girls who are seeking a big sister's advice. She could even be considered a milder Lady Gaga, considering her costumes and bisexual curiosity.

But enough of what she could be and on to what she is. Perry is, through these lyrics, a girl who has been hurt by a man she loved. Perry is now a strong woman who "used to be a shell".

Perry has attitude. She has something to say and she's going to make sure you hear it.

Teenage Dream is a strong follow-up to One of the Boys. Perry still maintains her cutesie sweetness and it seems almost as if Perry is permanently stuck in her teenage years. It's hard to believe that such a fun-loving party girl with a juvenile state of mind is going to be a married woman soon.

"Not Like the Movies" is one of my favorite tracks on this album. Here, Perry gets more personal than ever before, with lyrics describing a first sexual encounter that is nothing like fairy tales promised. It hurts, physically and emotionally, and now she knows when she will be ready for the right one because now she knows what not being ready feels like. Her breathy sadness here will touch you and make you remember feelings you may have long forgotten.

"Hummingbird Heartbeat" is a rocker akin to "Waking Up in Vegas" from her first album, only with the last remaining traces of innocence stripped clean. On "Circle the Drain", Perry expresses delicious anger. This is not a song you would want to blast at work. Well, unless explicit lyrics are allowed where you work. The title track has the hook to grab you in but it's inferior to some of the other work here. "Pearl" reminds me of "Dance in the Dark" by Lady Gaga since it is yet another song about a girl who has potential and a lot of life in her but is held down by the man in her life who fears her power.

"Who Am I Living For?" is an excellent display of Perry's vocals laced over that all-too-addictive Timbaland beat. This is my favorite track on the disc, hands down. "Peacock", however, is mainly a miss. At first listen, it reminded me of "Mickey" by Toni Basil if it was re-done by Gwen Stefani. A girl with her emotional depth does not need to rely on such a stupid expression of suggestion.

All in all, I think this is an excellent second album for Perry. She demonstrates growth here, a willingness to change her sound up without going overboard. If you liked the first album, I strongly suggest this one. And if you didn't, this album may just change your mind about her.

review_title: Cannonball Is A Master At Popularizing Jazz
review_text:
When I attended Harpur College(now called SUNY Binghamton) in 1962, the star act in the concert that proceeded the spring prom was Cannonball Adderly's Sextet with Yusef Lateef on tenor. I loved them! Wow, what a change occured the next year. Folk and rock music took over suddenly. So much for jazz.
I say all this to emphasize the fact that Cannonball's reception in 1962 was warm. He and his group not only played the best swinging straight ahead jazz, but Cannon used his warm personality to speak between numbers to explain and expound upon the meaning behind the music. This is very different from many jazz musicians who were mute. You were lucky if they announced the title of the song, let alone any other info.
On this recording, you get the live experience of Cannon and his groups recorded between 1967 and 1968 on Alan Grant's live radio broadcasts from the legendary Half Note club in NYC. It is enjoyable music. The quintet with Nat Adderly on cornet is on half the numbers, and half are by the quintet with Charles Lloyd on tenor. Joe Zawinul ably mans the piano, and Sam Jones is on bass. Roy McCurdy is on drums with the quintet, and Louis Hayes is on drums with the sextet.
I especially liked the quintet's romping version of "Fiddler on The Roof."
There is also one quartet number with Cannon and the rhythm section playing a lovely version of "Stars Fell on Alabama."
The sound is as expected on a radio broadcast. And you have to expect some numbers ending abruptly before the group has finished, presumably to align with the air time of a radio station.
I found this recording in a cut out bin for a couple of bucks. It was a good investment. This same recording is also available released by a different label. You can find reviews of it on Amazon. The recordings are identical.
Cannonball fans, and any jazz lover, can't go wrong with this recording.

This CD, being A/D/D from a previous recording made in the early 80's, is pretty awful acoustically-- in fact, at times the acoustics is just awful,-- but musically one can hear the startling promise of a huge rising star, that eventually exploded to form the constellation of Russian National Orchestra, of numerous groundbreaking glorious classical music recordings in the 90's and in the new millenium, and so forth.

I was turned onto it by a "RARE!" Youtube video of a "Young Pletnev Playing Liszt's Mephisto Valse" in Tokyo in the early 80's. Pletnev looked so young in the video and his playing in this CD sounds so young too, yet so passionate and exquisitely beautiful and gifted as to have moved me to tears of revelation, I must admit...

Pletnev never recorded Liszt's Mephisto Waltz again. Maybe he does not like it? Maybe the piece is too emotional for him personally? He's now 52. Maybe he is saving it to be recorded in the future so as to bring a more mature, seasoned, 21st-century, and fresh interpretation to it in his later years? I am looking very forward to his playing it again! To first see him play this powerful emotional piece by Liszt on Youtube and decades later to see him play it live in a concert hall would be an ultimate moving experience to me.

Meanwhile, I am looking forward to any Pletnev's new recording.

review_title: Don't let the word "disco" scare you. This is a good solid album
review_text:
Years before this album, Percy Faith was one of the true kings of instrumental pop music, especially with his Latin-flavored signature style, and admirers of his most classic works are likely to put off by this album just by seeing "disco" and "Percy Faith" in the same sentence (anybody remember Pat Boone and his heavy metal)?

Truth be told, nothing on this album (which was made just a year before Faith's death) is as richly beautiful as "Theme From A Summer Place" or "Delicado," but anyone who thinks that it's an album full of generic dance music made to cash in on the disco craze will be surprised. There is no singing, and all of the songs are solid, well-arranged, and have that rich, orchestral aura to them that Percy Faith is best known for.

review_text:
I have ordered this Shredded Beef in Broth a couple of times now. Twelve, 7 ounce packets make for good portion sizes. 1 pack provides plenty for a couple of hearty eaters. I'm surprised by all the negative reviews, but it appears that those are several months old. When I am reading reviews I often make sure to sort by "most recent" as sometimes recipes, formulas, or other pertinent info changes.

I am truly pleased with this Hereford product. It has a natural taste, smells good, and it tastes fine direct from pouch or heated up (my picture is of a portion of the pouch-- maybe 1/3 to 1/2 of contents). Appears like a thin block of meat at first, but it totally becomes a nice bowl of juicy shreds once heated. Not too salty, just enough to make it tasty direct from pouch. Do what you want with it. I tried it with crackers.

Great option for those that dont have time or interest to cook beef. Or want smaller portion sizes to work from. Shelf stable until opened, so that further lends to the convenience. Also good for those that want the beef but not the gravy. I really can't see any need for improvement. Not sure what else can be done (still thinking about some of the comments). It is only shredded beef, some broth (just a little, you are paying for beef here, yay!), and some salt.

Are you a prepper (proactive and ready for sudden food needs?) Super amazing for stacking up food for emergencies, mega inflation, shortages and such. Adds variety (only so much chicken and tuna one can eat), and it makes it easy. Dont even need a can opener. Can be shared with furry family members in a pinch too.

I would add this to my hiking bag for sure. Or even as an MRE to stash in my car or BOB or GHB (bug out bag, get home bag respectively).

I also buy their packets of [[ASIN:B096G7FZJZ meatballs in spaghetti sauce]] here, and their corned beef which I get elsewhere.

review_text:
May totally have spoilers here. I don't even know what the blurb for this book is at this point... I've read them all back to back and haven't bothered with blurbs. The books have been so alluring, it didn't matter the story, I knew I wanted to read them and come into the world of the Rogue Protectors.

Overall, a great story! But. Yes, there's a but on this one... This book had a couple of things that made me cringe a little.
For one, the pregnancy timeline didn't always add up. When she found out she was pregnant, she was saying she was only two weeks pregnant. But, anyone who has been pregnant should know they typically use your last cycle as the date. So by the time she tested on the day she was due, or the next day (I can't remember which it was) she would be 4 weeks by default of her cycle (there was nothing to indicate she's irregular and in fact it sounded like she was regular which is why she tested when she did. So there's that. And then a couple weeks later she goes to see the spook doctor in the non descript building who put her appropriately around 6 weeks. But then a chapter later or so, Nadia was saying she was 5 weeks. So yeah. The timeline was a bit odd/off for me. If I had never been pregnant before, it may not have even phased me. But having been pregnant twice and having a child, it made me cringe.
The second "blunder" to me was when Nadia was unconscious in the hospital and John was there dealing with doctors and such and the book said Nadia thought the other guy was a doctor... Except she was allegedly unconscious at that point so that didn't make sense.
The only other "negative" feedback would be referring to all the people. Having read all the books, and knowing who was around, I followed the story for the most part (sometimes even I didn't know which spy they were talking about. Haha). But referring to Andrade as "the businessman" and "the billionaire" in the book made me have to think of who is the businessman? Because they were also talking about Migs and Roarke and Levi and the MoMoS (I loved them!!). So name clarification at times, instead of "roles" (i.e., spy, businessman, etc.) would have been a bit easier to follow at times.

Ok, but back to John and Nadia. I loved how possessive he was with her and how he kept everything so nonchalant when he was abducted. Though I was a bit disappointed that Nadia didn't give him a thorough exam after finding out he was abducted so she could kiss his bruises and make him better. Hehe.

The MoMoS were amazing as well! Seriously, those guys rocked! I loved all of them! They made the story that much better. And then the Scot kicking butt and taking names?! Yes, please! His new romance with Fiona (John's mom) was adorable too. I'd have liked to see that more solid in the epilogue too.

John bring a spook definitely created challenges for his personal life, but it was lovely to see how Nadia pulled him out of that a bit and into the world of having it all - family, friends as family, and love.

Seriously, I'm not sure why you're reading this review. You should be reading the books and loving the MoMoS and all the other characters too!

We found that the game is a lot more fun if you add house rules to increase the number of item cards in play. For example, we play where everyone draws a new item card at the start of each round.
